  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - BARD</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>FIVE-SONG TWIST (YES, IT'S POSSIBLE, JUST HARD)</font> - <small>Flarestar, Luclin</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>There had been rumors of bards being able to twist more than 3 songs together at once.  Those rumors are true. Let me explain how.<P>
<P>
As you know, bardic songs hold for a certain number of ticks.  This works slightly differently than reported.  Everyone quotes the time as fifteen seconds for a song's effect, when it's really eighteen.  You're forgetting to count the second where it actually pulses.  All songs themselves take three seconds to sing before they take effect.  I've only done it using my 128K ISDN line... I can't do it with only one 64K channel or using a 56K modem, the lag throws you off too much.<P>
<P>
The trick to it is completely dependent on your lag.  With lag under 300, you can reliably do it assuming you don't lose track.  Initiate your first song.  As soon as three seconds have passed after started the song, switch to the next, regardless of whether you've gotten the message.  The song WILL work.  The worst that will happen is that the first song's effect will die maybe a split second before it's renewed.  If it's done properly, you can have five song effects going constantly, and assuming you choose the proper songs, your bard will more than outrank virtually any other class.<P>
<P>
A rather good combination to use with it when grouping is DDD, CoD, Anthem, Psalm of Cooling/Warmth, and of course Hymn of Restoration.  I'd suggest setting your bard to auto-follow a tank if you do this, though... you literally have to concentrate almost solely on twisting.  The good part is that by combining those you're doing a rather large amount of damage with the DoTs, and if they hit you they get hurt even more.  It takes a lot of speed and concentration to perfect this, but your bard's combat ability both solo and grouping increases massively.</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>Strategy Submitted on: Wednesday, March 01, 2000</td></tr>
